This review for Bruxie is long overdue, since it is probably one of my favorite places to eat anywhere in California.  One of the few places that actually live up to, and actually exceed the hype surrounding it.  I think the best compliment I can pay to Bruxie is that I live about 90 miles away, and I would (and have) driven here just to eat their waffle sandwiches.  I definitely make a stop here every time I'm either in or passing through OC.   The service here is always as great as the food, and the last time I was here solidified my faith in the place.  I brought a few friends here who had never tried Bruxie, and I had raved about the place for several months to them.  We got here and while waiting in line one of the employees told us about a pulled-pork waffle sandwich they had as a special.  Everyone decided to try the pulled-pork and they all really enjoyed it.  At the end of our meal the manager (I think her name was Amanda) asked how we enjoyed the meal.  Everyone said they loved it, as did I, and I also told her that my favorite waffle sandwich was the fried chicken and that I was disappointed that my friends did not order that one since it is the greatest sandwich in the world.  Five minutes later, Amanda came back out with a fried chicken sandwich for all my friends to try, free of charge.  She also included a bottle of their maple syrup for the sandwich which usually costs extra.  All of my friends loved the chicken sandwich.  More importantly though was how awesome the customer service was and the friendly gesture made by the manager.  I think more businesses would be successful if they had this type of customer service.  All of my friends remembered the great service we had and several of them have taken their families back since I introduced them to Bruxie.  I hope other restaurants take note, that this type of service (not necessarily just the freebie aspect) is how you develop recurring customer. One of the best (and probably worst) things about Bruxie is their constantly changing seasonal sandwiches, which make me keep coming back to try different things.  The only down-side is that when I fall in love with a new Bruxie sandwich, like their pumpkin pie Bruxie they had around Thanksgiving, I am disappointed when it is soon gone from the menu.  Oh well, this is probably why they developed a cult of followers that keep coming back to try all the limited edition menu items. The restaurant itself is nothing special to look at, just a shack with a handful of outdoor tables.  They just recently finally built a restroom, and added a few more seats.  Not an ideal place to go when it's raining, but I have soldiered through rain and hail to satisfy my addiction.  Also, be prepared to walk a few blocks to get here since most of the nearby residential streets are permit parking only.  Despite some of the minor obstacles to getting here, Bruxie is always worth it.
