I came here on the first week it opened, when no one had heard of it. It was a simple shack, with only a couple workers, including a nice manager/cook who talked with me about how they bring in the ice cream from Wisconsin and even gave me a free cup as a sample. And then the business exploded. Now they've upgraded the shack immensely. They have a large staff, a constantly transforming menu of specials, and a ridiculously long line of customers to match.  It's a great place to stop by if you're in the area. But I would not recommend going far out of your way for Bruxie alone. Here's what I think of the sandwiches: Buttermilk Fried Chicken and Waffle: The "safe bet" whenever I need to recommend a sandwich to a friend, especially one who loves American food. Good amount of chicken. The chili honey is light, clear, mildly sweet sauce. Green Eggs and Ham: A well-rounded and moderately filling sandwich. The eggs inside are omelette style, very clean. The basil pesto is delicious and spread in just the right amount. The amount of ham given is abundant. Smoked Salmon and Dill Cream Cheese: Very refreshing. Cucumbers are sliced thinly and spread evenly in the sandwich. I would like more salmon, but the portions help in making this a light choice. You won't feel bloated after this sandwich. Proscuitto and Gruyere: Another excellent "light" choice that will satisfy you without leaving you bloated, like the Smoked Salmon. The quality of the meat and cheese is good. Braised Beef Rib: Not bad; it's one of the heavier sandwiches. Lots of beef with lots of onions, and two waffles fries already in the waffle sandwich. The horseradish sticks onto the fries too much to be enjoyed with everything else - I would have preferred if they spread it more evenly. Patty Melt: Fantastic. Beef is a perfect medium rare patty that is juicy and thick. Plenty of carmelized onions. Sauce tastes like 1000 islands. I would love it if they made this a regular on the menu. Strawberry Cheesecake: I thought this would be a real cheesecake. It's actually a waffle sandwich. A strawberry lover's dream, but barely any cheesecake. Ogura Sandwich: Red beans are a staple in the Asian dessert world and I'm happy to see them make an appearance on the Bruxie menu. A note about parking. It's pretty much all street parking, which is a hot mess. Don't waste your time and cause congestion looking for parking near the shop. Look for places a block away instead, and walk there. It's a nice, brisk stroll. Seating is limited too. Keep that in mind.
