Nearly 15 months have passed since Bruxie's grand opening and my initial review in November 2010.  Since then, Bruxie has improved their food, expanded their menu, developed the dining area, opened a second location in downtown Brea and was even listed as one Yelp's most popular restaurants of 2011.  Yup, the little waffle shack by Chapman University has done pretty well for itself.   RECOMMENDATIONS (ranked from most favorite to least favorite) Bruxie Burger - Angus beef patty with cheddar cheese, sliced tomatoes, pickles, mayo and crispy lettuce.  Yeah, it's basically just a cheeseburger... but it's a cheeseburger in a waffle.  And it works! Bacon, Egg & Cheddar - Tilamook cheddar, mayo, applewood smoked bacon.  It's everything you could want in a breakfast, once again, in a waffle!  Pure genius!    Add ketchup or hot sauce to your liking.   Buttermilk Fried Chicken & Waffle - Served with chili honey and cole slaw.  I remember when they first served this, the piece of chicken was rather dinky.  Not anymore.  Now it's bigger, juicer and a must try.  However, I still think its ridiculous to charge $1 for maple syrup. Hot Pastrami (seasonal favorite) - Boar's head pastrami, Gruyere cheese, spicy brown mustard, cider slaw and half sour pickles.  I wasn't sure if this would work, but it did.  Mustard was a little strong though and I prefer mine without pickles. PASS ON THESE (in no particular order): Pulled Pork (daily special) - Interesting idea, but the the pork is super bland.  It could be great with BBQ sauce, but then it probably wouldn't work with the waffle at all. Lobster Salad (seasonal favorite) - Had this as a 4th of July special served with fries for $17.76.  I love lobster but this was way too expensive and the lobster had absolutely no flavor.  Huge miss. Smoked Salmon & Dill Cream Cheese - Herb cream cheese, cucumbers and chives.  Loved the idea, but it just doesn't work on a waffle. SIDES Waffle Fries - Who doesn't love fries?  Add them to your combo to save money. Irish Nachos (seasonal favorite) - Waffle fries, cheese sauce, sour cream, bacon and chives.  Pretty good, but the cheese sauce could be better. DESSERT Seasonal Crème Brûlée - Classic vanilla creme with burnt raw sugar and seasonal fresh fruit (strawberries or bananas).  The only sweet waffle I recommend. Frozen Custard - Soft serve Wisconsin frozen custard.  It's a rich fresh ice cream enhanced with egg yolks.  It's thicker, creamier and probably a lot more calories than regular ice cream.  Yum! CONCLUSION The truth is that Bruxie is probably the most hyped restaurant ever.  However, the hype wouldn't exist without a solid product.  A lot of their sandwiches are hits, but a lot are misses too.  You just have to find the Bruxie for you.
