Best affordable waffles of anywhere, and this place sits in the backyard of Chapman University.  As such, you get lots of co-eds that come through here. I would come here for dessert.  The savory menu isn't really tailored to my taste.  The burger patty in the waffle burger is good, but the combination isn't super flattering.  Same thing goes for the chicken and waffle item.  If you're expecting something like Roscoe's, this chicky/waffle combo is a continent apart.  They put slaw and de-boned fried chicken and wrap the waffle around it.  The waffle is likely to split in half from the moisture, with the slaw spilling onto the plate.  I can't exactly fancy the idea of pouring Cholula hot sauce in this "chicken waffle taco in a split shell" deal.  I ended up eat the chicken and the waffle as separates.   Actually, the combination of burger, or chicken, salmon, or any other masks the brilliance of the waffle.  It is fluffy, and when eaten by itself, the subtle but elegant aroma is just so pleasant as it gets a chance to stand out.  Whatever the batter they're using hits the spot. The "waffle fries" don't seem to be too different from what you can get from Chick-fil-A or Carl's Jr.  In my opinion, they could use a bit of extra time in the fryer for added crispiness.   For desserts, I've tried the smores waffle and the Nutella waffle with hints of sugar cinnamon.  Both are delightful in their own way.  Smores is warm and gooey chocolate marshmellow convenience sandwiched in the amazing waffles.  For the Nutella, it comes in a plastic condiment cup, so that you can spread it on to your taste. This place is casual, and it's very much like a food stand, with all outdoor seating and a small parking lot.  I give this place a "D" for health.  The sandwich meal items are heavy.  But once in a while, you might feeling a craving and want to spoil yourself.   If I was in the area, I'd stop by just for the waffles by itself.
